\subsection{\href{https://beta.lmfdb.org/knowledge/show/group.almost_simple}{Almost simple group}}
\begin{definition}\label{group.almost_simple}
\uses{group.automorphism,group.quasisimple,group.simple}
An \textbf{almost simple group} is a group $G$ that lies between a non-abelian \hyperref[group.simple]{simple} group $S$ and its \hyperref[group.automorphism]{automorphism} group Aut$(S)$, i.e. $S \subseteq G \subseteq $Aut$(S).$

Every non-abelian simple group is almost simple, but it is not implied by $G$ being \hyperref[group.quasisimple]{quasisimple}, as shown by <a href="{{url\_for('abstract.index')}}?almost\_simple=yes&quasisimple=no">these examples</a>.
\end{definition}


